This songs on this recording span over half a millennium, and reflect both
 monophonic and polyphonic written and oral traditions but they all share
 a common ancestry.
 They are steeped in a vernacular tradition and a belief as old as the Tuscan
 language in the power of that language to describe and praise the divine.
 And many ancient and beautiful things are contained within this language:
 the fresh vision and invigorating devotional spirit of the mendicant orders,
 the oratorical spirit of the Tuscan communes, the earthy directness of
 merchants and artisans, the deep civic charity of the confraternities and
 hospitals, the vivid and compelling imagery of mendicant sermons, and the
 native talents and spontanaiety of the civic improvvisatori.
 Deepest within and inseparable from the language, are the melodies and
 the latent power of these seemingly semple songs is released only by those
 who understand that with each performance there is the opportunity to recreate
 not only the song itsself, but the ancient and potent devotional spirit
 that animates each one.
